# Kamal evaluates this file with shell semantics. Lines look like
# KEY=value_or_$(expression). Working directory is infra/kamal/.
#
# No actual secret values live here — only references. Safe to commit.
#
# Source of secrets:
#   Bitwarden Secrets Manager  → app + accessory passwords (BWS_PROJECT_ID/all)
#   Tofu state (encrypted)     → Cloudflare tunnel token + R2 S3 keys
#   gh CLI (fallback only)     → GHCR registry password if no INFRA_GHCR_TOKEN in BWS
#
# BWS_PROJECT_ID and BWS_ACCESS_TOKEN come from infra/.env via Make's export.

# One bulk fetch of every secret in the project — Kamal's native
# bitwarden-sm adapter shells out to `bws secret list` once and caches the
# JSON in $SECRETS. Per-key `extract` calls are local string ops, not HTTP.
SECRETS=$(kamal secrets fetch --adapter bitwarden-sm --from $BWS_PROJECT_ID all)

# Tofu state is encrypted (see infra/tofu/versions.tf). TF_VAR_state_passphrase
# is injected by `bin/with-secrets` (the Makefile wraps `kamal` in it), so
# every `$(tofu output …)` subshell below inherits it from the parent kamal
# process — Kamal evaluates each substitution in a fresh /bin/sh, but that
# child sh DOES inherit the parent's env.

# Cloudflare tunnel token: Tofu-managed (rotation via `tofu apply
# -replace=…`; storing in BWS would duplicate source of truth).
TUNNEL_TOKEN=$(tofu -chdir=../tofu output -raw tunnel_token 2>/dev/null)

# GHCR: dedicated `write:packages` PAT, stored in BWS as INFRA_GHCR_TOKEN.
# CI uses the SAME BWS value (BWS_ACCESS_TOKEN is set on the runner, the
# bws CLI fetches INFRA_GHCR_TOKEN like every other secret). DO NOT use a
# `${VAR:-default}` pattern here — Kamal's secrets-file parser handles $()
# substitution but mangles ${VAR:-default} (strips `${VAR`, leaves the
# `:-default}` literally as the value, which docker login then rejects).
# Plain $() only. First-time setup: see docs/deploy.md for the bws-secret-create step.
KAMAL_REGISTRY_PASSWORD=$(kamal secrets extract INFRA_GHCR_TOKEN $SECRETS)

# App + accessory secrets — extracted from the bulk BWS fetch.
# Each product has its own Better Auth instance; BWS holds a separate
# random value per product so a compromise of one doesn't affect the other.
BETTER_AUTH_SECRET=$(kamal secrets extract MENU_AUTH_SECRET $SECRETS)
POSTGRES_PASSWORD=$(kamal secrets extract INFRA_POSTGRES_PASSWORD $SECRETS)
DATABASE_URL=postgres://postgres:$POSTGRES_PASSWORD@infra-postgres:5432/menu

# Menu's OAuth client identity at genkan. Stored in BWS as
# MENU_OAUTH_CLIENT_{ID,SECRET}; aliased to GENKAN_OAUTH_CLIENT_* on this
# side so better-auth's generic-oauth plugin reads the right env-var names.
GENKAN_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID=$(kamal secrets extract MENU_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID $SECRETS)
GENKAN_OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET=$(kamal secrets extract MENU_OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET $SECRETS)

# App asset storage — Cloudflare R2 via the assets-scoped Tofu token.
# S3_ENDPOINT + S3_BUCKET + S3_PUBLIC_URL come from Tofu outputs; the keys
# are derived from the scoped API token (id + sha256(value)).
S3_ENDPOINT=$(tofu -chdir=../tofu output -raw assets_endpoint 2>/dev/null)
S3_REGION=auto
S3_BUCKET=$(tofu -chdir=../tofu output -raw assets_bucket_name 2>/dev/null)
S3_ACCESS_KEY=$(tofu -chdir=../tofu output -raw assets_r2_access_key_id 2>/dev/null)
S3_SECRET_KEY=$(tofu -chdir=../tofu output -raw assets_r2_secret_access_key 2>/dev/null)
S3_PUBLIC_URL=$(tofu -chdir=../tofu output -raw assets_public_url 2>/dev/null)
